Great. Great. Thank you so much for that introduction.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:04:00.000
I'm really happy to be here and to be talking about tidy models and why I have been really glad to work on this project.

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:13.000
Three things that you might keep in mind that if you run into your work or you start to get concerned about in your particular domain, that you might then think,

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:18.000
ah, I should think about using tidy models to solve this kind of problem.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:30.000
So I'm going to start by giving just a little bit of background of, like, who, like, where I came from and how I came to kind of work on many of these kinds of tools.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:34.000
So my academic background is physics and astronomy.

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:47.000
I have a Ph.D. in astrophysics, and I was in research, eventually left academia, and then went on a little bit of a winding path of, like, what am I going to do now?

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:50.000
Now that I'm, like, exited academia.

00:04:50.000 --> 00:05:03.000
And around the time when this was happening in my own life and career, we really were seeing this growth in, like, this newish at the time field, data science.

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:12.000
And people who are coming into these kinds of roles were coming in from kind of backgrounds that were weird in the way that my background was weird.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:23.000
So I come to the practice of data work, the practice of machine learning, not so much from a statistical background.

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:32.000
Like, I'm not one of these people that has, like, really solid academic statistical knowledge or theoretical statistical knowledge.

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:41.000
And I'm not someone also who comes to my work as a data science practitioner from a software engineering background.

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:53.000
Instead, I come as, like, oh, let me come and, like, pick up these skills as I'm preparing for jobs or, like, on the job somewhere.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:55.000
Can I learn about this?

00:05:55.000 --> 00:06:06.000
And can I think about it as someone who is really concerned with process, with systems, and, like, how things work together?

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:16.000
I love thinking about people's really practical problems and how they solve them, like, really applied kind of work.

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:23.000
So I worked as a data scientist in a couple of different organizations.

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:33.000
And then starting about three and a half years ago, I was hired at then our studio, would now Posit.

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:36.000
And I was hired to work on open source software.

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:42.000
So I contributed to open source software kind of on the side, right, like as many of us do.

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:44.000
And we have regular jobs.

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:49.000
And so going to work at our studio, formerly our studio, now Posit,

00:06:49.000 --> 00:07:00.000
this was a shift from being someone who was largely a practitioner and built some tooling on the side to think about tooling as a focus

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:08.000
and then kind of keep my hand in on, like, data science practice as I think about how people engage in these tasks.

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:13.000
I was hired to our studio to work on tidy models.

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:19.000
So tidy models started, you know, maybe a couple years before I started being engaged in it.

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:22.000
But by the time I joined, things were really coming together.

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:31.000
Things were really get, like, pretty much ready for people to engage and use tidy models in their real work.

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:39.000
So, like, we started saying things like, well, if you're using something else, like Carrot in your project, you know,

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:42.000
no reason to rewrite it from scratch.

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:48.000
But if you're starting a new project, we recommend, you know, you check out tidy models and see if it will be good.

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:53.000
It was very interesting because I had engaged in machine learning before in some of my jobs.

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:59.000
But, like, you know, I did not come from an academic statistics background.

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:06.000
And so it was really interesting to get thrown into this tooling, the tooling for machine learning

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:10.000
and thinking about what people, sets people up for success.

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:16.000
So I'm, if you, you know, we love thinking about, like, what is machine learning?

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:20.000
Like, thinking, like, okay, what, when I hear this, what is going on?

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:29.000
And, you know, this, of course, a very wonderful and delightful SKCD about, that gives us, like, an insight into, like,

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:33.000
what is it that we mean when we say machine learning?

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:41.000
You know, we, so we're using data, we're using, like, big piles of data to give us some kind of answers,

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:44.000
to give us some kind of prediction.

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:54.000
So instead of maybe coding decisions, like, with SL statements or something,

00:08:54.000 --> 00:09:02.000
instead we use data and use statistical methods to learn patterns from the data to be able to give us some kind of an answer.

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:07.000
So, you know, these kind of, it's interesting to be talking about this right now,

00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:12.000
because over the past, you know, year, six months, two months, you know, we see,

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:20.000
we see talk about what is, like, what is AI and this word being used so much more broadly.

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:33.000
So traditionally, AI would be the biggest outside category and includes both making decisions,

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:38.000
you learn from data, and setting up, like, rules-based AI.

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:44.000
So being, say, picture yourself, a picture of yourself, the sort of, if we see this big,

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:48.000
we would, if we say that's artificial intelligence for some definition of artificial intelligence,

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:55.000
we can have one approach that is, I'm going to code a huge set of rules.

00:09:55.000 --> 00:09:57.000
If this happens, do this.

00:09:57.000 --> 00:09:58.000
If this happens, do this.

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:01.000
And, like, code the rules directly.

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:07.000
Another approach is to take a huge data set of chess games that exist,

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:15.000
and we then put it all into some kind of statistical learning algorithm,

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:20.000
and then we let a model learn how to play chess from the data that we have.

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:27.000
So we have the big category, traditionally, of AI, which traditionally includes rules-based

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:31.000
and machine learning, meaning we learn from data.

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:35.000
And then inside of that, there's different kinds of machine learning.

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:41.000
So the kind that, you know, if you're hearing about in the news that are, you know,

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:45.000
like driving these changes in large language models,

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:49.000
they're all the way inside of that deep learning circle.

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:53.000
The work that I'm going to talk about is in a little bit different place.

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:57.000
It is in that place where it says dozens of different ML methods.

00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:02.000
Depending on the kind of data you have and the kind of problems you're trying to look at,

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:07.000
that's actually where a huge amount of business value comes from,

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:12.000
is in that place where it says dozens of different machine learning methods.

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:17.000
Of course, we're seeing lots of people be really excited about generating value

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:20.000
from things over there in, like, the deep learning category,

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:24.000
but you do have to have specific kinds of data

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:29.000
and some kind of very large volumes of data to be able to make use of that.

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:35.000
So we're specifically going to focus down into that place where it says dozens of different ML methods.

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:39.000
Another way to think about this kind of, which you might call classical machine learning,

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:47.000
so that's kind of in contrast to deep learning methods, which are, I guess we can say, newer.

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:50.000
We generally categorize things into two places.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:54.000
So unsupervised is when your data doesn't have a label.

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:58.000
So you might do things like dimensionality reduction there,

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:00.000
where you say – look at examples.

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:05.000
It says, like, okay, you've got clothes.

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:08.000
Maybe I want to cluster data.

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:13.000
I have different kinds of clothes, and I want to look at the – none of the clothes have labels.

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:15.000
I don't know which kind of clothes are which,

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:19.000
but I want to use the characteristics of the clothes to clump them into a cluster.

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:24.000
So, say, I'm going to put the pants together with the shorts with the leggings,

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:27.000
and I'm going to put the dresses with the jumpsuits.

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:29.000
So, like, learn how things go together.

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:32.000
But I don't have – in that case, I don't have any labels.

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:35.000
I don't know – I don't have something I'm trying to predict.

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:39.000
On the other side, supervised machine learning, then, for sure, the data –

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:42.000
the idea there is the data has a label.

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:48.000
That label typically is either a category or a number.

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:54.000
So when we have – let's say we've got socks, and we want to divide them up by color.

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:58.000
So we see here on that little visual, we're going to, like, divide the apples from the pears.

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:06.000
The other kind of supervised – the most common kind of supervised problem is regression,

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:08.000
where we're predicting a number.

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:10.000
So we can predict a category or predict a number.

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:13.000
The kind of work that I am going to be talking about here – this is all kind of like,

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:17.000
what are we even talking about – is over on the left-hand side.

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:26.000
So if you can formulate a scientific or business question as a supervised machine learning problem,

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:33.000
then there is a huge swath of tools that are out there to help you solve that.

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:37.000
So there's – you know, there's lots of different things that fall under the category of AI,

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:41.000
lots of different things that fall under the category of machine learning.

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:45.000
Supervised machine learning, either classification or regression,

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:55.000
are areas that have – that have huge infrastructure of methods and tools

00:13:55.000 --> 00:13:58.000
so that you can use that to solve some kind of a problem.

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:06.000
Specifically, we are going to talk about using tidy models to approach this kind of problem.

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:09.000
These – like, if you – hey, you've got a question or a problem,

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:12.000
can you formulate it as supervised machine learning?

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:16.000
Then you can use a tool for it, such as tidy models.

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:25.000
So the tidy models framework is a – you can think of it as analogous to the Tidyverse.

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:28.000
So it's a collection of R packages.

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:33.000
So if you think about the Tidyverse being used for data manipulation,

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:39.000
data visualization, reshaping of data, munging of data, dealing with CSV files,

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:46.000
dealing with dates, you know, the tidy models framework is an analogy

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:53.000
where all these different packages are focused on a different part of the machine learning process

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:57.000
with a specific focus on supervised machine learning.

00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:03.000
So if you can install the tidy models metapackage, and then just like, you know,

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:09.000
if you have done library tidyverse and then you've gotten ggplot2, dplyr, tidy R,

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:15.000
if you do library tidy models, you get a bunch of packages that get, you know,

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:19.000
attached there so that you can use the functions from them.

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:27.000
So I would first say if it feels overwhelming to get started to know there's a bunch of packages

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:32.000
and to not be sure which functions come from which individual package,

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:38.000
I would say try to step back from that feeling of discomfort and just kind of go with it.

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:45.000
Like, just – like, don't stress out too much if you don't know which functions come from which packages.

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:50.000
That's definitely something that comes as you get more experience using something.

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:55.000
So maybe when you started, like, using tidyverse, maybe you felt, you know,

00:15:55.000 --> 00:16:00.000
maybe you're like, oh, gosh, is – where is the function coalesce from?

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:04.000
Or where – like, oh, I think I saw people, like, talking about pivot wider and pivot longer.

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:07.000
Is that in dplyr? Is that in tidy R?

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:10.000
Like, no – try not to be super stressed about that,

00:16:11.000 --> 00:16:16.000
but to know it's a meta – it's a meta package with individual packages in it,

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:19.000
and those individual packages are focused.

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:25.000
The reason why – so it actually is better for us, the maintainers of tidy models,

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:27.000
to have things modular like this.

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:32.000
Also, it turns out, it's better for you to have the things more modular.

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:37.000
It's better for maintenance because if each of these packages is separate,

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:40.000
if you need to change something about, say, tuning,

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:45.000
which you probably guess is for the tune package, so hyperparameter tuning for models,

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:47.000
you only have to change it there.

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:50.000
You can have smaller changes.

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:53.000
It's easier to do releases when things are more modular.

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:55.000
You probably experience in your own work.

00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:59.000
And when you make pieces of code more modular, things are better

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:05.000
versus, like, one giant kind of thing that can get hard to deal with.

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:06.000
So it's better for maintenance.

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:11.000
It's also better for you because it turns out if you want to do –

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:14.000
you know, if you want to do, like, deploy a model,

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:19.000
you don't need the example data that, you know, we use in all our packages.

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:24.000
You don't need – you know, you don't need the tuning infrastructure, probably,

00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:26.000
if it's time for you to deploy a model.

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:32.000
So it helps you be a – to adopt better practices in your machine learning

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:35.000
when you have these modular pieces.

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:37.000
So let's look at a couple of these names.

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:44.000
So yardstick is a package for measuring how models are doing.

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:46.000
It's a package for model metrics.

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:48.000
So yardstick is – you know,

00:17:48.000 --> 00:17:51.000
you probably don't have to worry too much about knowing these individual things,

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:55.000
but yardstick is the package that has all the metrics that we use

00:17:55.000 --> 00:17:57.000
to see how something is going.

00:17:57.000 --> 00:18:02.000
Tune, like I said, is a package for hyperparameter tuning.

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:08.000
And so what I'm going to do today is to focus on a couple of these packages

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:14.000
and to frame it in you thinking about – you thinking about,

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:18.000
if I run into a problem like X, what can I reach for

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:22.000
and what kind of problems does Tiny Models solve for me?

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:24.000
So we're going to talk about three topics,

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:26.000
three things that we're going to go through for today.

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:30.000
So the first one, we're going to talk about what makes a model,

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:33.000
like what actually is a model, what are the components of it,

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:36.000
like what can we use to define a model.

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:40.000
We're going to talk about spending your data budget wisely,

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:45.000
how to be a good steward of the amount of data that you have.

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:50.000
And then we're going to wrap up by talking about how we can build better features

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:52.000
for machine learning.

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:57.000
So these are the three topics that we're going to walk through.

00:18:57.000 --> 00:19:02.000
All right, so let's start with the first one, what makes a model.

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:09.000
So in R, modeling is really heterogeneous.

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:16.000
It's like really, really mixed up, really, really –

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:21.000
there are dramatic differences around model interfaces,

00:19:21.000 --> 00:19:26.000
how you go about fitting a model, and like what the execution kind of strategy is.

00:19:26.000 --> 00:19:29.000
So this is a lot less true in Python.

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:32.000
So in Python, there is scikit-learn,

00:19:32.000 --> 00:19:38.000
which you have access to many kinds of models within scikit-learn.

00:19:38.000 --> 00:19:45.000
In R, R has more, you know, statisticians in it, like working with it.

00:19:45.000 --> 00:19:52.000
And so there's a real strength in R is that there's a huge diversity

00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:54.000
of different kinds of models.

00:19:54.000 --> 00:19:57.000
They can live quite separately from each other.

00:19:57.000 --> 00:20:03.000
On the downside, it means if you were to pick up some package for modeling,

00:20:03.000 --> 00:20:08.000
the way that you go about like fitting

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:12.000
and maybe executing a model can be extremely different

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:16.000
from the next modeling package that you fit up.

00:20:16.000 --> 00:20:22.000
So in R, the model, the norm is kind of that things are quite broken up.

00:20:22.000 --> 00:20:24.000
There's lots of packages and like the –

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:28.000
say if you wanted to change from random forest to XGBoost,

00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:31.000
like you go to a whole different package because the implementations

00:20:31.000 --> 00:20:35.000
for those two things don't live in the same piece of software.

00:20:35.000 --> 00:20:40.000
There have been several kind of attempts

00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:45.000
or try to kind of make a more unified kind of thing.

00:20:45.000 --> 00:20:49.000
If you ever have heard of CARET, the CARET package, C-A-R-E-T,

00:20:49.000 --> 00:20:52.000
that was by Max, my co-author on the book.

00:20:52.000 --> 00:20:57.000
And it was kind of like a first go to make a more scikit-learn-like interface

00:20:57.000 --> 00:20:58.000
to models.

00:20:58.000 --> 00:21:04.000
There's also MLR and currently like MLR3.

00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:07.000
They're kind of on their second iteration of like – or third, I don't know –

00:21:07.000 --> 00:21:11.000
of like how to go about making like a unified kind of interface

00:21:11.000 --> 00:21:14.000
to many kinds of models.

00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:17.000
So part of TidyModels was approaching –

00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:21.000
like the part of the motivating why bother like doing TidyModels

00:21:21.000 --> 00:21:28.000
is to approach this very question and give a new answer,

00:21:28.000 --> 00:21:33.000
kind of like a modern answer, a Tidyverse-inspired answer

00:21:33.000 --> 00:21:36.000
to like how – what are we going to do when –

00:21:36.000 --> 00:21:40.000
like I have to rewrite all my code if I want to change

00:21:40.000 --> 00:21:42.000
from one kind of model to another.

00:21:42.000 --> 00:21:47.000
So the package that approaches this is called Parsnip.

00:21:47.000 --> 00:21:52.000
So it's a – you know, it is a little bit of a joke, right, compared to CARET,

00:21:52.000 --> 00:21:56.000
like the idea of like – although that CARET is not spelled like the vegetable,

00:21:56.000 --> 00:21:59.000
but so that's where this kind of like pun or joke comes through.

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:00.000
It's like another vegetable.

00:22:00.000 --> 00:22:06.000
So the Parsnip package is the package for setting up model specifications.

00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:11.000
And in TidyModels, there are three components

00:22:11.000 --> 00:22:15.000
to completely specifying what a model is like.

00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:17.000
The first one we might use the word model for,

00:22:17.000 --> 00:22:19.000
but what this means – we'll get into it a little bit,

00:22:19.000 --> 00:22:24.000
but this is like what kind of statistical algorithm is it.

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:31.000
The second stage is to specify an engine, and the third is to set the mode,

00:22:31.000 --> 00:22:35.000
the mode of what kind of model that you need to have.

00:22:35.000 --> 00:22:36.000
So let's walk through these.

00:22:36.000 --> 00:22:44.000
So first, model here means what kind of mapping are we going to make

00:22:44.000 --> 00:22:51.000
to get from our inputs to our outputs, like our predictors to our prediction.

00:22:51.000 --> 00:22:53.000
How do we get from our predictors to our prediction?

00:22:53.000 --> 00:22:56.000
How do we get from our inputs to our outputs?

00:22:56.000 --> 00:23:02.000
So one kind of model is linear regression, regular old OLS.

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:07.000
So here I can set up a model specification here

00:23:07.000 --> 00:23:11.000
by using the function linear reg, linear reg here.

00:23:11.000 --> 00:23:16.000
So there's lots of different kinds of things.

00:23:16.000 --> 00:23:20.000
A model – different model types.

00:23:20.000 --> 00:23:23.000
You might say model type, model algorithm.

00:23:23.000 --> 00:23:27.000
You know, we can – it's random forest is another one that I already mentioned.

00:23:27.000 --> 00:23:31.000
Like it's a different way of getting from the inputs to the outputs.

00:23:31.000 --> 00:23:33.000
Next we need to say an engine.

00:23:33.000 --> 00:23:38.000
So back here you can see it says computational engine LM

00:23:38.000 --> 00:23:41.000
because it turns out there are some defaults.

00:23:41.000 --> 00:23:43.000
But you don't have to just use the defaults.

00:23:43.000 --> 00:23:48.000
In fact, you can set your own engines, the engine that is right for you.

00:23:48.000 --> 00:23:53.000
So here instead of before it said – notice here it says computational engine LM.

00:23:53.000 --> 00:23:57.000
Here I'm saying computational engine Glymnet.

00:23:57.000 --> 00:24:02.000
So this is an R package.

00:24:02.000 --> 00:24:07.000
So when I say LM, it's going to do ordinary least squares.

00:24:07.000 --> 00:24:11.000
It's going to use the built-in LM function that comes with R in the stats package.

00:24:11.000 --> 00:24:16.000
If I say set engine Glymnet, then it's going to do regularized regression

00:24:16.000 --> 00:24:19.000
using the R package Glymnet.

00:24:19.000 --> 00:24:27.000
So engine, think about it as – it's not about the algorithm that's being used.

00:24:27.000 --> 00:24:32.000
Instead, it is about what computational engine am I going to use

00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:40.000
to implement that computational algorithm or type, model type.

00:24:40.000 --> 00:24:45.000
So here the first two that I told you about are both R.

00:24:45.000 --> 00:24:47.000
But not all engines are R.

00:24:47.000 --> 00:24:50.000
So we can also use SAN here.

00:24:50.000 --> 00:24:57.000
And here what we'll make is we'll use a Bayesian linear model

00:24:57.000 --> 00:25:01.000
implemented in the Bayesian engine SAN.

00:25:01.000 --> 00:25:04.000
So the engines can be things like R packages.

00:25:04.000 --> 00:25:07.000
They can be things where we're calling out not –

00:25:07.000 --> 00:25:10.000
what's actually doing the computation is not R at all,

00:25:10.000 --> 00:25:13.000
but rather I believe SAN is in C++.

00:25:13.000 --> 00:25:16.000
We can do things like Spark where it's doing off-host execution.

00:25:16.000 --> 00:25:21.000
So we separate out you deciding what kind of model type

00:25:21.000 --> 00:25:25.000
or model algorithm you're going to use from how that engine is implemented.

00:25:25.000 --> 00:25:29.000
And, of course, the idea here is that we're going to give a unified interface

00:25:29.000 --> 00:25:34.000
to all of them so that you can not have to change everything about your code

00:25:34.000 --> 00:25:42.000
if you want to switch from using, say, LM on your laptop to Spark in a Spark cluster.

00:25:42.000 --> 00:25:45.000
So next we need to set a mode.

00:25:45.000 --> 00:25:50.000
So notice here that it says regression in all of these here

00:25:50.000 --> 00:25:58.000
because it turns out linear regression, the model always is predicting a number.

00:25:58.000 --> 00:26:00.000
It's always predicting a continuous property.

00:26:00.000 --> 00:26:10.000
But some model types, some model algorithms don't have to only do one kind of output.

00:26:10.000 --> 00:26:13.000
So an example of that is a decision tree.

00:26:13.000 --> 00:26:17.000
So if I call just the function decision tree here,

00:26:17.000 --> 00:26:21.000
you can see it has a default computational engine.

00:26:21.000 --> 00:26:26.000
R part is an R package that is used that has an implementation of decision trees.

00:26:26.000 --> 00:26:31.000
But notice it says unknown mode because a decision tree can be used

00:26:31.000 --> 00:26:37.000
for regression or classification.

00:26:37.000 --> 00:26:41.000
When I first learned about this, I was confused because the idea of a decision tree

00:26:41.000 --> 00:26:44.000
being used to predict a number was confusing to me.

00:26:44.000 --> 00:26:48.000
But, you know, it depends on how complicated your tree is,

00:26:48.000 --> 00:26:53.000
like how smooth of a set of outputs that you can get.

00:26:53.000 --> 00:26:58.000
So decision trees can predict either regression or classification.

00:26:58.000 --> 00:27:02.000
And the way that we do that is we set the mode.

00:27:02.000 --> 00:27:09.000
So we can set the mode as regression here if we have a numeric continuous output,

00:27:09.000 --> 00:27:14.000
or we can set the mode as classification if we have a categorical output

00:27:14.000 --> 00:27:18.000
where we're going to predict yes versus no or red versus blue

00:27:18.000 --> 00:27:21.000
or some category versus a continuous one.

00:27:21.000 --> 00:27:26.000
So all of the models are available.

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:27.000
Whoops.

00:27:27.000 --> 00:27:28.000
Let me see.

00:27:28.000 --> 00:27:29.000
Can I?

00:27:29.000 --> 00:27:30.000
No, I can't.

00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:31.000
Oh, my gosh.

00:27:31.000 --> 00:27:32.000
I can't copy it.

00:27:32.000 --> 00:27:33.000
Okay.

00:27:33.000 --> 00:27:34.000
Sorry.

00:27:34.000 --> 00:27:35.000
I'll drop the links later.

00:27:35.000 --> 00:27:39.000
So if you go to tidymodels.org slash find slash parsnip,

00:27:39.000 --> 00:27:42.000
there's a list of all available models.

00:27:42.000 --> 00:27:44.000
And what you can do is you can, you know,

00:27:44.000 --> 00:27:50.000
search and sort and see what is there and what is appropriate to your use case.

00:27:50.000 --> 00:27:58.000
So these are the three pieces that the three components or aspects of a model

00:27:58.000 --> 00:28:03.000
that make up a model specification in Tidy Models.

00:28:03.000 --> 00:28:08.000
The reason why these three are the ones that are required is because that's what

00:28:08.000 --> 00:28:13.000
we need to kind of fully specify what kind of model you need to do.

00:28:13.000 --> 00:28:18.000
And a reason why you might decide to use Tidy Models is because you don't

00:28:18.000 --> 00:28:23.000
necessarily know ahead of time what kind of model algorithm is going to be the

00:28:23.000 --> 00:28:26.000
best fit for your particular use case.

00:28:26.000 --> 00:28:29.000
And, in fact, you want to try a bunch.

00:28:29.000 --> 00:28:31.000
You want to try more than one, maybe a lot.

00:28:31.000 --> 00:28:34.000
And if you use Tidy Models,

00:28:34.000 --> 00:28:39.000
that allows you to pretty fluently change from one kind of model algorithm to

00:28:39.000 --> 00:28:41.000
another.

00:28:41.000 --> 00:28:44.000
By contrast, if you are someone who's like, I only ever use LM,

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:47.000
LM solves all my problems and is good enough,

00:28:47.000 --> 00:28:51.000
then you're probably in a situation where Tidy Models is not going to help you

00:28:51.000 --> 00:28:55.000
that much, where working with using Tidy Models is not, you know,

00:28:55.000 --> 00:28:59.000
maybe not necessary, maybe not that important.

00:28:59.000 --> 00:29:03.000
Another piece of this, what makes a model specification,

00:29:03.000 --> 00:29:08.000
is about the interface to these different models.

00:29:08.000 --> 00:29:16.000
So what we have here is three different implementations for boosted trees.

00:29:16.000 --> 00:29:23.000
So the XGBoost implementation, the C5O implementation for boosted trees,

00:29:23.000 --> 00:29:26.000
and the Spark implementation for boosted trees.

00:29:26.000 --> 00:29:33.000
So they all are implementing the same or close to the same algorithm,

00:29:33.000 --> 00:29:35.000
where you make a tree, a decision tree.

00:29:35.000 --> 00:29:37.000
You train it on some of the data.

00:29:37.000 --> 00:29:39.000
You use that result there to make the next one.

00:29:39.000 --> 00:29:40.000
You do it again.

00:29:40.000 --> 00:29:41.000
You, like, boost the tree.

00:29:41.000 --> 00:29:43.000
So you, like, take a bunch of weak learners,

00:29:43.000 --> 00:29:46.000
and you put them together to make a strong learner.

00:29:46.000 --> 00:29:55.000
The thing is, they all have different names for the arguments that are

00:29:55.000 --> 00:29:57.000
actually the same thing.

00:29:57.000 --> 00:29:59.000
Like, look at that trees one.

00:29:59.000 --> 00:30:03.000
That's when you're making a boosted tree model like XGBoost does

00:30:03.000 --> 00:30:07.000
or like the Spark boosted tree thing does.

00:30:07.000 --> 00:30:10.000
There is a number of trees.

00:30:10.000 --> 00:30:12.000
Like, how many trees are you going to have?

00:30:12.000 --> 00:30:16.000
In XGBoost, that number is called n rounds,

00:30:16.000 --> 00:30:19.000
meaning how many rounds of boosting are you going to do.

00:30:19.000 --> 00:30:21.000
In C5O, it's called trials.

00:30:21.000 --> 00:30:23.000
In Spark, it's called max iter,

00:30:23.000 --> 00:30:27.000
like what's the maximum number of iterations will go through to boost things.

00:30:27.000 --> 00:30:31.000
I find it kind of overwhelming if I wanted to switch from, like,

00:30:31.000 --> 00:30:35.000
XGBoost to Spark to try and figure out how these map to each other,

00:30:35.000 --> 00:30:37.000
like how these things map to each other,

00:30:37.000 --> 00:30:41.000
so that you can do an apples-to-apples comparison or, you know.

00:30:41.000 --> 00:30:46.000
So another thing that Parsnip offers you is a unified interface.

00:30:46.000 --> 00:30:52.000
We will admit it's another set of names, right, for all of these things.

00:30:52.000 --> 00:30:57.000
But it is one set of names to interface to all of them.

00:30:57.000 --> 00:30:59.000
So you only have to know trees

00:30:59.000 --> 00:31:04.000
instead of knowing all the individual different kinds of names.

00:31:04.000 --> 00:31:06.000
So this is another reason.

00:31:06.000 --> 00:31:08.000
So if you think about what kind of problem am I working on,

00:31:08.000 --> 00:31:11.000
do I need to try different implementations

00:31:11.000 --> 00:31:14.000
to be able to know what the best option might be?

00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:16.000
If you are in that situation,

00:31:16.000 --> 00:31:20.000
then tidy models can be a great fit for you.

00:31:21.000 --> 00:31:25.000
All right, let's move on to the second reason to use tidy models,

00:31:25.000 --> 00:31:28.000
the second sort of thing you might be faced with that you might think,

00:31:28.000 --> 00:31:31.000
okay, I want to do – I need to do this.

00:31:31.000 --> 00:31:33.000
How am I going to go about doing it?

00:31:33.000 --> 00:31:37.000
It's this idea of spending your data budget.

00:31:37.000 --> 00:31:42.000
When you work with – when it's time to approach some modeling problem,

00:31:42.000 --> 00:31:46.000
some machine learning problem, you have a certain amount of data.

00:31:46.000 --> 00:31:50.000
And, you know, in most of our situations, it's not infinite, right?

00:31:50.000 --> 00:31:51.000
You have a certain amount,

00:31:51.000 --> 00:31:57.000
and you want to do a good job of using it to get the best results that you can

00:31:57.000 --> 00:32:00.000
from the limited data that you have.

00:32:00.000 --> 00:32:04.000
So the package in tidy models that handles this data budget,

00:32:04.000 --> 00:32:08.000
these data budget kind of tasks, is called RSample.

00:32:08.000 --> 00:32:11.000
So it's like a shortening of resample.

00:32:11.000 --> 00:32:16.000
So it's tools for data splitting and data resampling.

00:32:16.000 --> 00:32:19.000
So let's start with data splitting.

00:32:19.000 --> 00:32:24.000
So I bet many of you are familiar with this idea of splitting your data

00:32:24.000 --> 00:32:27.000
into training and testing.

00:32:27.000 --> 00:32:31.000
So you have some original quantity of data,

00:32:31.000 --> 00:32:36.000
and you need to split it randomly, typically,

00:32:36.000 --> 00:32:39.000
and you're going to keep some of your data.

00:32:39.000 --> 00:32:42.000
You're going to use to estimate the model parameters.

00:32:42.000 --> 00:32:44.000
You're going to use for learning.

00:32:44.000 --> 00:32:50.000
Another piece of the data you are going to use to estimate how well the model

00:32:50.000 --> 00:32:52.000
is performing.

00:32:52.000 --> 00:32:57.000
So it's not used for learning, but instead for prediction only,

00:32:57.000 --> 00:32:59.000
for estimating performance only.

00:32:59.000 --> 00:33:01.000
And we want those totally separate.

00:33:01.000 --> 00:33:05.000
We do not want to reuse – we do not want to use that testing data

00:33:05.000 --> 00:33:08.000
for any important things.

00:33:08.000 --> 00:33:13.000
So Tidy Models, of course, provides fluent tools for these kinds of splitting.

00:33:13.000 --> 00:33:19.000
So here I've just got a quick little example data set here that's housing

00:33:19.000 --> 00:33:23.000
prices in Sacramento, California.

00:33:23.000 --> 00:33:26.000
And here if I take that original data set that I have

00:33:26.000 --> 00:33:28.000
and I use initial split,

00:33:28.000 --> 00:33:34.000
what I have is a split object that keeps track of which of my observations went

00:33:34.000 --> 00:33:37.000
into training and which of them went into testing.

00:33:38.000 --> 00:33:44.000
Once I have that split object, I can operate on it to get out what I need.

00:33:44.000 --> 00:33:48.000
So if I called training on the split object,

00:33:48.000 --> 00:33:53.000
I get out those 699 houses that are in my training set.

00:33:53.000 --> 00:33:58.000
If I call testing, I get the other ones that are in my testing set.

00:33:58.000 --> 00:34:04.000
So the idea here, you use the training data only during the process

00:34:04.000 --> 00:34:09.000
of model development and only at the very end to use the testing data.

00:34:09.000 --> 00:34:12.000
In fact, we would think – we would say, like,

00:34:12.000 --> 00:34:15.000
the testing data was extremely precious.

00:34:15.000 --> 00:34:18.000
We can't go about just, like, spending it willy-nilly.

00:34:18.000 --> 00:34:25.000
The purpose of the testing set is to estimate your performance on new data,

00:34:25.000 --> 00:34:31.000
to do a final check on did my model – is my model performing the way

00:34:31.000 --> 00:34:33.000
that I thought it did.

00:34:33.000 --> 00:34:37.000
So that all sounds well and good, you know, great, training, testing.

00:34:37.000 --> 00:34:44.000
But I just said a little bit ago that we might want to try a whole bunch

00:34:44.000 --> 00:34:45.000
of different models.

00:34:45.000 --> 00:34:49.000
We might want to – we might want to try XGBlues,

00:34:49.000 --> 00:34:52.000
Juice, plus Random Forest, plus Glimnet.

00:34:52.000 --> 00:34:54.000
I might want to try a lot of different things

00:34:54.000 --> 00:34:57.000
and see how they compare to each other.

00:34:57.000 --> 00:34:58.000
So what do I do?

00:34:58.000 --> 00:35:00.000
What do I do in this situation?

00:35:01.000 --> 00:35:06.000
If I use the testing set to compare the performance for four or five models,

00:35:06.000 --> 00:35:08.000
I am up a creek.

00:35:08.000 --> 00:35:11.000
That is a bad decision, and I am in no good situation.

00:35:11.000 --> 00:35:14.000
I can't compare four or five different models.

00:35:14.000 --> 00:35:17.000
XGBlues needs to be tuned.

00:35:17.000 --> 00:35:21.000
There's a bunch of hyperparameters, and we have to try a bunch of different –

00:35:21.000 --> 00:35:24.000
there's no way to know what those hyperparameters should be

00:35:24.000 --> 00:35:26.000
from training the model one time.

00:35:26.000 --> 00:35:30.000
Instead, I have to train it a bunch of times on different model configurations

00:35:30.000 --> 00:35:32.000
and see which one is best.

00:35:32.000 --> 00:35:33.000
How do I decide?

00:35:33.000 --> 00:35:35.000
What data do I use to see which one is best?

00:35:35.000 --> 00:35:41.000
If I use the training set, I get an overly optimistic view.

00:35:41.000 --> 00:35:45.000
And, in fact, if I – depending on how my training split, I can get a wrong –

00:35:45.000 --> 00:35:48.000
I can get a wrong answer depending on exactly which observations

00:35:48.000 --> 00:35:50.000
are in the training set.

00:35:50.000 --> 00:35:54.000
So the answer to this is resampling.

00:35:54.000 --> 00:35:58.000
So what we will do is we have our all data to start with.

00:35:58.000 --> 00:36:01.000
We divide into training and testing.

00:36:01.000 --> 00:36:05.000
And that testing data just stay – is set aside.

00:36:05.000 --> 00:36:07.000
Think of it as precious.

00:36:07.000 --> 00:36:11.000
We do not touch it until the very end of our model development process.

00:36:11.000 --> 00:36:18.000
And, instead, we resample our training set to create little simulated versions

00:36:18.000 --> 00:36:20.000
of that training set.

00:36:20.000 --> 00:36:24.000
So for each resample, I divide into an analysis set,

00:36:24.000 --> 00:36:28.000
which is an analog of training data, and my assessment set,

00:36:28.000 --> 00:36:31.000
which is an analog of the testing data.

00:36:31.000 --> 00:36:35.000
And I can use all those resamples for hyperparameter tuning

00:36:35.000 --> 00:36:37.000
or to do something like comparing.

00:36:37.000 --> 00:36:42.000
Say I want to compare random forest with glimnet with a decision tree.

00:36:42.000 --> 00:36:45.000
I want to compare them all and see which one is best.

00:36:45.000 --> 00:36:50.000
And we do that by using our resamples, using all of them

00:36:50.000 --> 00:36:53.000
and then aggregating the results there.

00:36:53.000 --> 00:37:00.000
There's a huge number of ways to make resamples of how to divide up your data.

00:37:00.000 --> 00:37:03.000
One of them is called – one of the most common

00:37:03.000 --> 00:37:07.000
and great default kind of one is cross-validation.

00:37:07.000 --> 00:37:13.000
So if I – the way cross-validation works is that I have my pile of data,

00:37:13.000 --> 00:37:15.000
my pile of observations.

00:37:15.000 --> 00:37:18.000
In this example, it is the training set there,

00:37:18.000 --> 00:37:23.000
that yellow-orange pentagon-y thing, that training set.

00:37:23.000 --> 00:37:26.000
So these 30 things are the training set.

00:37:26.000 --> 00:37:31.000
And I can randomly split them up into a number of folds.

00:37:31.000 --> 00:37:35.000
So here we're doing three for this example.

00:37:35.000 --> 00:37:40.000
And so I randomly assign as I go along which one goes into which fold,

00:37:41.000 --> 00:37:46.000
yeah, into which fold, and then I divide them out so that in fold one,

00:37:46.000 --> 00:37:52.000
the first time I go through, I hold out one-third of the data,

00:37:52.000 --> 00:37:57.000
and the other two-thirds go into the analysis set.

00:37:57.000 --> 00:38:02.000
So notice I'm going to fit the model using two-thirds of the data in this case,

00:38:02.000 --> 00:38:06.000
and then I will estimate performance using held-out data

00:38:06.000 --> 00:38:09.000
that was not used in the performance.

00:38:09.000 --> 00:38:14.000
So here where it says estimate performance using as we go along there,

00:38:14.000 --> 00:38:16.000
that's the equivalent of the assessment set.

00:38:16.000 --> 00:38:18.000
It's like a little test set.

00:38:18.000 --> 00:38:20.000
It is not used to train.

00:38:20.000 --> 00:38:24.000
It is instead used to measure performance, the test.

00:38:24.000 --> 00:38:30.000
So in the second fold, we hold out a different set, one-third,

00:38:30.000 --> 00:38:31.000
and train on the other two-thirds.

00:38:31.000 --> 00:38:35.000
On the third fold, we hold out the last third and do this.

00:38:35.000 --> 00:38:37.000
So this is how cross-validation works.

00:38:37.000 --> 00:38:42.000
In tidy models, the function for it, it's called vfoldcv,

00:38:42.000 --> 00:38:44.000
and the default is actually to make 10 splits,

00:38:44.000 --> 00:38:48.000
because it turns out that works great for many situations.

00:38:48.000 --> 00:38:55.000
If you have the amount of data that you should be doing cross-validation,

00:38:55.000 --> 00:38:56.000
10 is a good default.

00:38:56.000 --> 00:39:00.000
You notice here this might be a little too small for cross-validation

00:39:00.000 --> 00:39:04.000
because I don't have that many observations in my little test sets there

00:39:04.000 --> 00:39:05.000
and my assessment sets.

00:39:05.000 --> 00:39:11.000
So I might, for this data, I want to think about a different approach.

00:39:11.000 --> 00:39:13.000
But let's talk about what it is.

00:39:13.000 --> 00:39:19.000
So we have the same amount of testing data, sorry, training data,

00:39:19.000 --> 00:39:23.000
and then we make 10 different resamples from it.

00:39:23.000 --> 00:39:27.000
We divide it into 10 pieces, and then we hold out the first,

00:39:27.000 --> 00:39:31.000
use the other nine-tenths, hold out the second, use the other nine-tenths,

00:39:31.000 --> 00:39:33.000
hold out the third, and so forth.

00:39:33.000 --> 00:39:35.000
That's how we make these cross-validation resamples.

00:39:35.000 --> 00:39:42.000
What this lets us do is to use the training set for tuning,

00:39:42.000 --> 00:39:44.000
for comparing models, for making decisions,

00:39:44.000 --> 00:39:48.000
before having that very precious test set at the end.

00:39:48.000 --> 00:39:51.000
For something like this, it might be a better idea,

00:39:51.000 --> 00:39:53.000
for a smallish data set like this,

00:39:53.000 --> 00:39:56.000
it might be a better idea to use a different approach for resampling,

00:39:56.000 --> 00:39:58.000
like bootstrapping.

00:39:58.000 --> 00:40:03.000
So it is a different way of making these kinds of resamples.

00:40:03.000 --> 00:40:07.000
This approach is, again, showing an example of three.

00:40:07.000 --> 00:40:16.000
So the idea is you take your original training set that had 30 in this

00:40:16.000 --> 00:40:18.000
example, 30 examples in it,

00:40:18.000 --> 00:40:23.000
and you draw with replacements until you get to 30 again.

00:40:23.000 --> 00:40:27.000
So notice that in the first bootstrap iteration,

00:40:27.000 --> 00:40:32.000
the first observation is in there twice.

00:40:32.000 --> 00:40:39.000
So you draw with replacement so that it goes back into the bucket before

00:40:39.000 --> 00:40:40.000
you take another one.

00:40:40.000 --> 00:40:42.000
So back in the bucket, you take another one.

00:40:42.000 --> 00:40:45.000
So in the second one, notice three is in there three times.

00:40:45.000 --> 00:40:46.000
That can definitely happen.

00:40:46.000 --> 00:40:48.000
And then whatever doesn't get picked,

00:40:49.000 --> 00:40:54.000
whatever doesn't get picked to go into the analysis set,

00:40:54.000 --> 00:40:57.000
that goes into the assessment set.

00:40:57.000 --> 00:41:01.000
So here we are always going to train on 30,

00:41:01.000 --> 00:41:04.000
and then we will estimate performance on, you know,

00:41:04.000 --> 00:41:08.000
whatever kind of number, you know, is leftover,

00:41:08.000 --> 00:41:10.000
whatever the leftovers are there.

00:41:10.000 --> 00:41:13.000
So bootstrapping, the default, you know, here's the function for that.

00:41:13.000 --> 00:41:16.000
Bootstrapping, the default is 25, bigger.

00:41:16.000 --> 00:41:19.000
And you can see that for my smaller data set,

00:41:19.000 --> 00:41:21.000
this seems like a better idea.

00:41:21.000 --> 00:41:25.000
So cross-validation and bootstrap resampling,

00:41:25.000 --> 00:41:32.000
they have different kind of questions,

00:41:32.000 --> 00:41:37.000
or different kind of bias-variance tradeoffs is what it comes down to.

00:41:37.000 --> 00:41:40.000
So it can be a good choice in different situations.

00:41:40.000 --> 00:41:44.000
Let's see, do you have a question about what I'm talking about right now?

