But there's one relevant to what you're presenting right now.

00:41:52.000 --> 00:41:58.000
How does the setC function ensure that we can create reproducibility?

00:41:58.000 --> 00:41:59.000
Yeah, great.

00:41:59.000 --> 00:42:01.000
Yeah, so these all involve randomness, right?

00:42:01.000 --> 00:42:08.000
Like we're pulling from these distributions randomly.

00:42:09.000 --> 00:42:14.000
And so if you ran this, and then, well, I have a setC here.

00:42:14.000 --> 00:42:22.000
And so what that means is that you will get the same result every time

00:42:22.000 --> 00:42:25.000
that you run this, if you run these together with setC.

00:42:25.000 --> 00:42:27.000
Here, oh, I have setC there too.

00:42:27.000 --> 00:42:29.000
But if you were to not run with setC,

00:42:29.000 --> 00:42:32.000
if you were just to call bootstraps, bootstraps, bootstraps,

00:42:32.000 --> 00:42:35.000
like you would get different versions every time.

00:42:35.000 --> 00:42:41.000
Now, we would hope we're using robust enough statistical methods

00:42:41.000 --> 00:42:43.000
that we're not seeing huge differences.

00:42:43.000 --> 00:42:46.000
Like we pick a totally different model if we set the seed,

00:42:46.000 --> 00:42:47.000
if we set the seed different.

00:42:47.000 --> 00:42:49.000
That means something's wrong, right?

00:42:49.000 --> 00:42:54.000
Like if you choose a totally different model, if you set a different seed,

00:42:54.000 --> 00:42:58.000
that means something's not going great.

00:42:58.000 --> 00:43:03.000
However, it always is a good idea to set your seed when you have randomness,

00:43:03.000 --> 00:43:06.000
just so that you get the same answer that you get the next time,

00:43:06.000 --> 00:43:11.000
like down to the same like exact numeric answer versus being like, oh, my gosh,

00:43:11.000 --> 00:43:16.000
my metrics are a little bit different this time than what I got last time.

00:43:16.000 --> 00:43:20.000
So great question about reproducibility and setting a seed.

00:43:20.000 --> 00:43:23.000
So that number there, 1, 2, 3, is not a special number.

00:43:23.000 --> 00:43:27.000
Like I could put, you know, the year I was born, this year.

00:43:27.000 --> 00:43:30.000
You know, like I can put any kind of number there.

00:43:30.000 --> 00:43:33.000
But what it does is it sets the random number generator.

00:43:33.000 --> 00:43:37.000
So computers have a hard time making random numbers,

00:43:37.000 --> 00:43:40.000
but we have these algorithms that give us close to,

00:43:40.000 --> 00:43:43.000
as close as possible to truly random numbers.

00:43:43.000 --> 00:43:49.000
And it's a stream, like R has a random number generator stream.

00:43:49.000 --> 00:43:52.000
So if you've ever seen RNG stream, that's what that means.

00:43:52.000 --> 00:43:56.000
It's like the stream of random numbers.

00:43:56.000 --> 00:43:58.000
Now, if you don't set the seed,

00:43:58.000 --> 00:44:01.000
the next time you go into the stream and say, give me a random number,

00:44:01.000 --> 00:44:02.000
you'll get the next one.

00:44:02.000 --> 00:44:04.000
Whereas if you do set the seed,

00:44:04.000 --> 00:44:08.000
you always start at the same place in the random number generator seed,

00:44:08.000 --> 00:44:12.000
which is not like you would be bad if you got a totally different result at the

00:44:12.000 --> 00:44:14.000
end, like you chose a different model.

00:44:14.000 --> 00:44:19.000
But it's still helpful in the process of model development so that you get the

00:44:19.000 --> 00:44:21.000
same answers every time.

00:44:21.000 --> 00:44:22.000
All right.

00:44:22.000 --> 00:44:24.000
So there's lots of different resampling methods.

00:44:25.000 --> 00:44:30.000
And what these allow you to do is to spend your data wisely.

00:44:30.000 --> 00:44:32.000
You have a certain amount of data,

00:44:32.000 --> 00:44:37.000
and then you need to make the best decisions possible about how to spend it.

00:44:37.000 --> 00:44:41.000
You spend some data on model estimation,

00:44:41.000 --> 00:44:44.000
on learning those parameters of that model,

00:44:44.000 --> 00:44:46.000
whether it's XGBoost or linear regression.

00:44:46.000 --> 00:44:52.000
And then you spend other data on how is that model performing?

00:44:52.000 --> 00:44:53.000
How is that model performing?

00:44:53.000 --> 00:44:54.000
I have to know.

00:44:54.000 --> 00:44:58.000
I can't use the same data that I use for training because you can memorize

00:44:58.000 --> 00:44:59.000
that data.

00:44:59.000 --> 00:45:02.000
These different kinds of – so, like,

00:45:02.000 --> 00:45:07.000
really good options include cross-validation.

00:45:07.000 --> 00:45:09.000
So that's that V full CV.

00:45:09.000 --> 00:45:12.000
Bootstraps are a really great option.

00:45:12.000 --> 00:45:14.000
You can do Monte Carlo.

00:45:14.000 --> 00:45:15.000
It's okay, right?

00:45:15.000 --> 00:45:16.000
Leave one out.

00:45:16.000 --> 00:45:19.000
Cross-validation is maybe not the best option.

00:45:19.000 --> 00:45:20.000
But it is there as an option.

00:45:21.000 --> 00:45:23.000
If you have a ton of data, just a ton,

00:45:23.000 --> 00:45:26.000
then a validation split can be a good option.

00:45:26.000 --> 00:45:32.000
So that's basically picture this image, but you just have one of those.

00:45:32.000 --> 00:45:37.000
You just – instead of having B, see how it says resample one, resample two,

00:45:37.000 --> 00:45:41.000
resample B, instead of doing it, you just do one split.

00:45:41.000 --> 00:45:48.000
And then you can use that validation set to tune, to choose models.

00:45:49.000 --> 00:45:53.000
And so here, pictures are just being one row instead of ten rows

00:45:53.000 --> 00:45:55.000
or 25 rows, just one row.

00:45:55.000 --> 00:46:00.000
And that can work if you have so much data that it is a waste of time to do

00:46:00.000 --> 00:46:04.000
things ten times because you get a good estimate of how well a model is

00:46:04.000 --> 00:46:08.000
performing with one assessment set.

00:46:08.000 --> 00:46:13.000
Okay, so we talked about building models.

00:46:13.000 --> 00:46:16.000
Like, you may choose to use tidy models because you need to try a bunch

00:46:16.000 --> 00:46:17.000
of different models.

00:46:17.000 --> 00:46:22.000
You may choose to use tidy models because your data budget is limited

00:46:22.000 --> 00:46:28.000
and you want to use good statistical practices to spend your data in a wise way.

00:46:28.000 --> 00:46:32.000
Tidy models provide you with these tools and guardrails,

00:46:32.000 --> 00:46:37.000
like when it comes time to fit, to tune, to – we're about to talk about

00:46:37.000 --> 00:46:38.000
feature engineering.

00:46:38.000 --> 00:46:40.000
When it comes time to do all these things,

00:46:40.000 --> 00:46:44.000
tidy models provide you with tools and guardrails,

00:46:44.000 --> 00:46:48.000
like keeping you from doing the wrong thing in many situations so that you can

00:46:48.000 --> 00:46:51.000
spend your data budget wisely.

00:46:51.000 --> 00:46:54.000
The last of these three topics that I want to talk about,

00:46:54.000 --> 00:47:02.000
like why might you decide to use tidy models, is to build better features.

00:47:02.000 --> 00:47:07.000
So the package in tidy models that handles feature engineering is called

00:47:07.000 --> 00:47:08.000
Recipes.

00:47:08.000 --> 00:47:10.000
It's the Recipes package.

00:47:10.000 --> 00:47:16.000
And it uses a certain, I guess, analogy or metaphor for what feature

00:47:16.000 --> 00:47:17.000
engineering is like.

00:47:17.000 --> 00:47:25.000
So, you know, we use the phrase pre-processing kind of to be synonymous

00:47:25.000 --> 00:47:26.000
with feature engineering.

00:47:26.000 --> 00:47:31.000
Your data, you have data, and you need it to go into a model,

00:47:31.000 --> 00:47:34.000
but it's not quite ready to go into the model yet.

00:47:34.000 --> 00:47:38.000
You need to do some stuff first to it before it can go in.

00:47:39.000 --> 00:47:42.000
This is not so much data cleaning.

00:47:42.000 --> 00:47:49.000
So data pre-processing or feature engineering is different from data cleaning

00:47:49.000 --> 00:47:52.000
or more basic data preparation.

00:47:52.000 --> 00:47:57.000
Like if it's something that you could use dplyr to do, that's not really,

00:47:57.000 --> 00:47:59.000
like two lines of dplyr to do.

00:47:59.000 --> 00:48:02.000
That's not really what we mean by data pre-processing.

00:48:02.000 --> 00:48:07.000
Instead, we're mostly talking about statistical transformations of your data.

00:48:07.000 --> 00:48:10.000
So the analogy here is that you have a pantry,

00:48:10.000 --> 00:48:13.000
and in your pantry are various variables.

00:48:13.000 --> 00:48:15.000
They're like the ingredients.

00:48:15.000 --> 00:48:19.000
So the ingredients for your feature engineering are like those are the things

00:48:19.000 --> 00:48:20.000
you're starting with.

00:48:20.000 --> 00:48:23.000
You've got response, an outcome, an output.

00:48:23.000 --> 00:48:26.000
You've got predictors or inputs here.

00:48:26.000 --> 00:48:34.000
So we write a recipe that uses our ingredients, our components,

00:48:34.000 --> 00:48:36.000
our variables, and says what to do.

00:48:36.000 --> 00:48:39.000
And it's like a recipe like step one, step two, step three.

00:48:39.000 --> 00:48:42.000
So here, this little example, it's like first,

00:48:42.000 --> 00:48:48.000
I'm going to impute missing data using K nearest neighbors.

00:48:48.000 --> 00:48:51.000
Notice this is like a statistical transformation.

00:48:51.000 --> 00:48:52.000
We learn it.

00:48:52.000 --> 00:48:55.000
We learn it from training data.

00:48:55.000 --> 00:48:57.000
It's an unsupervised algorithm, actually,

00:48:57.000 --> 00:48:59.000
if you remember all the way back from the beginning.

00:48:59.000 --> 00:49:04.000
So we learn which, if there's missing data in some variable,

00:49:05.000 --> 00:49:09.000
which one is that most like with nearest neighbors?

00:49:09.000 --> 00:49:10.000
Let's put that value in there.

00:49:10.000 --> 00:49:12.000
Then it's step scale.

00:49:12.000 --> 00:49:18.000
So that's where you're dividing each of the variables by a standard deviation.

00:49:18.000 --> 00:49:20.000
So they all have standard deviation of one.

00:49:20.000 --> 00:49:23.000
Again, this is a learned statistical transformation.

00:49:23.000 --> 00:49:27.000
You use the training data to learn what the standard deviation is,

00:49:27.000 --> 00:49:29.000
then to divide.

00:49:30.000 --> 00:49:32.000
So you write out a recipe.

00:49:32.000 --> 00:49:37.000
Then you say, okay, here's some training data,

00:49:37.000 --> 00:49:42.000
and I'm going to learn what those transformations are.

00:49:42.000 --> 00:49:44.000
So that's what there is, number three.

00:49:44.000 --> 00:49:46.000
So number one is what are my variables.

00:49:46.000 --> 00:49:48.000
Number two is what's my recipe.

00:49:48.000 --> 00:49:49.000
Let's write it down.

00:49:49.000 --> 00:49:53.000
Number three is let me use my training data to learn those statistical

00:49:53.000 --> 00:49:54.000
transformations.

00:49:54.000 --> 00:49:58.000
And then number four is I can now apply this to other data.

00:49:58.000 --> 00:50:04.000
Say I could apply it to new data at prediction time.

00:50:04.000 --> 00:50:07.000
You can think about applying it to the testing data.

00:50:07.000 --> 00:50:11.000
Because these steps, especially these examples that are here,

00:50:11.000 --> 00:50:15.000
these steps learn from data.

00:50:15.000 --> 00:50:21.000
So imagine a situation where you used your whole training set to learn these,

00:50:21.000 --> 00:50:24.000
and then you try to estimate.

00:50:24.000 --> 00:50:27.000
You, again, were like, wait, how well did that work?

00:50:27.000 --> 00:50:31.000
So, again, you have to do this inside of a resampling loop.

00:50:31.000 --> 00:50:33.000
I don't mean literally you have to write a loop,

00:50:33.000 --> 00:50:39.000
but you have to use your resampled data for feature engineering just like you

00:50:39.000 --> 00:50:43.000
have to use your resampled data for model estimation.

00:50:43.000 --> 00:50:50.000
These count as parameters of your model broadly defined.

00:50:50.000 --> 00:50:53.000
They're not a parameter of the decision tree,

00:50:53.000 --> 00:50:55.000
but they're a parameter of the feature engineering,

00:50:55.000 --> 00:50:57.000
and they have to be learned.

00:50:57.000 --> 00:51:02.000
One reason to use tidy models is that it provides you with the guardrails

00:51:02.000 --> 00:51:06.000
and the tools to not have data leakage,

00:51:06.000 --> 00:51:12.000
to not have overly optimistic results from your feature engineering.

00:51:12.000 --> 00:51:16.000
So, I mean, I think in the machine learning practice world,

00:51:16.000 --> 00:51:22.000
not very many people are falling into traps anymore around, you know,

00:51:22.000 --> 00:51:25.000
training on the whole data set and not having an estimate of how it does at

00:51:25.000 --> 00:51:26.000
the end.

00:51:26.000 --> 00:51:32.000
But it's tricky to keep data leakage out of your feature engineering as well.

00:51:32.000 --> 00:51:34.000
So, there's good support for that here.

