and you can just like go through and, you know,

00:53:05.000 --> 00:53:07.000
you're not having to do much of this manually.

00:53:07.000 --> 00:53:10.000
Instead, you can specify it as a recipe.

00:53:10.000 --> 00:53:12.000
So, let's look at what that would look like.

00:53:12.000 --> 00:53:16.000
So, here is where we're taking our ingredients.

00:53:16.000 --> 00:53:21.000
So, if I've got that same Sacramento housing data I had before, I say, okay,

00:53:21.000 --> 00:53:26.000
my output, my outcome, my response, that's the price.

00:53:26.000 --> 00:53:28.000
That's the thing that I'm predicting.

00:53:28.000 --> 00:53:31.000
The input here used a dot, which means everything else.

00:53:31.000 --> 00:53:33.000
So, I start with my ingredients.

00:53:33.000 --> 00:53:37.000
So, price is going to explain everything else.

00:53:37.000 --> 00:53:41.000
And then I build my preprocessor step by step.

00:53:41.000 --> 00:53:48.000
So, here, what this first one does is if you have a factor and you see a new

00:53:48.000 --> 00:53:54.000
level in it at prediction time, this just kind of puts the mean in there.

00:53:54.000 --> 00:54:02.000
So, it's a handler for new levels and factors that you didn't see during

00:54:02.000 --> 00:54:04.000
training time.

00:54:04.000 --> 00:54:07.000
SEPDUMMY creates dummy or indicator variables.

00:54:07.000 --> 00:54:12.000
So, let's say that you have a bunch of factors and you need to convert them to

00:54:12.000 --> 00:54:15.000
indicator variables like a bunch of ones and zeros.

00:54:15.000 --> 00:54:17.000
This does that.

00:54:17.000 --> 00:54:20.000
SEPVV removes variables that have zero variance.

00:54:20.000 --> 00:54:24.000
So, models like, especially the linear models, behave very,

00:54:24.000 --> 00:54:29.000
like they can't converge if you have, they will error.

00:54:29.000 --> 00:54:32.000
If you have variables that have zero variance, meaning they're all the same

00:54:32.000 --> 00:54:40.000
value, like picture yourself doing resampling and you end up with a,

00:54:40.000 --> 00:54:43.000
like there's some factor in it that's, you know, red and blue.

00:54:43.000 --> 00:54:50.000
And you end up with all reds in one fold, one resampling fold.

00:54:50.000 --> 00:54:53.000
Then what this does is it removes that so that you don't,

00:54:53.000 --> 00:54:56.000
so that your model can fit anyway, even though that turned out that way.

00:54:56.000 --> 00:54:59.000
So, we basically, it's basically like all kinds of different,

00:54:59.000 --> 00:55:01.000
we just specify here, here, here.

00:55:01.000 --> 00:55:03.000
You do have to think about the order a little bit.

00:55:03.000 --> 00:55:08.000
Like, for example, you can't do SEPNOVEL after SEPDUMMY.

00:55:08.000 --> 00:55:12.000
Because SEPDUMMY means, what SEPVDUMMY does is it converts all your factor

00:55:12.000 --> 00:55:15.000
variables into numeric variables.

00:55:15.000 --> 00:55:18.000
So, if you did SEPNOVEL after, you know, it doesn't do anything

00:55:18.000 --> 00:55:20.000
because all your factor variables are gone.

00:55:20.000 --> 00:55:23.000
But that's the way recipes work, you know, like in real life,

00:55:23.000 --> 00:55:25.000
you have to do things in the right order.

00:55:25.000 --> 00:55:28.000
So, the analogy holds up fairly well there.

00:55:28.000 --> 00:55:31.000
You have to be thoughtful about the order in which you set up a recipe.

00:55:31.000 --> 00:55:34.000
So, I just showed you a couple.

00:55:34.000 --> 00:55:38.000
But there are a lot of different ways of doing this.

00:55:38.000 --> 00:55:41.000
So, you can, we have those categorical predictors,

00:55:41.000 --> 00:55:47.000
things like a predictor that say red, green, blue, or some kind of factor.

00:55:47.000 --> 00:55:51.000
You can encode those in various ways to numeric values.

00:55:52.000 --> 00:55:55.000
So, I talked about dummy or indicator variables.

00:55:55.000 --> 00:55:57.000
That's like everything to 1s and 0s.

00:55:57.000 --> 00:56:02.000
Like, if you have three levels, you go to three columns,

00:56:02.000 --> 00:56:06.000
and it's all like 1, 0, 0, 0, 1, 0, 0, 0, 1, like that.

00:56:06.000 --> 00:56:09.000
There's other ways of encoding categorical predictors,

00:56:09.000 --> 00:56:12.000
like using an effect encoding.

00:56:12.000 --> 00:56:16.000
That's like a supervised feature engineering approach,

00:56:16.000 --> 00:56:22.000
which, again, means you want to be really careful about how you use resampling

00:56:22.000 --> 00:56:24.000
to see how that goes.

00:56:24.000 --> 00:56:28.000
You know, real basic things, like centering and scaling variables.

00:56:28.000 --> 00:56:36.000
Some model estimation approaches need everything on the same scale.

00:56:36.000 --> 00:56:40.000
Anything, basically, that uses like a distance metric inside of it,

00:56:41.000 --> 00:56:46.000
nearest neighbor models are like this.

00:56:46.000 --> 00:56:48.000
Support vector machines are like this.

00:56:48.000 --> 00:56:52.000
They use a distance metric, so you need to have everything on the same scale.

00:56:52.000 --> 00:56:56.000
You got to handle class imbalance, like someone asked a question about.

00:56:56.000 --> 00:57:02.000
So, you know, if you have a very imbalanced kind of training set,

00:57:02.000 --> 00:57:06.000
where you have a lot of one class and very few of another class,

00:57:06.000 --> 00:57:10.000
you can handle that somewhere, either by upsampling the minority class

00:57:10.000 --> 00:57:13.000
or downsampling the majority class.

00:57:13.000 --> 00:57:18.000
And there are different algorithms to decide how exactly to go about doing that.

00:57:18.000 --> 00:57:21.000
Imputing missing data.

00:57:21.000 --> 00:57:24.000
If you have missing data, you don't have to throw it out,

00:57:24.000 --> 00:57:29.000
depending on if you have some missing data in your training set,

00:57:29.000 --> 00:57:32.000
in your data that you want to use for machine learning.

00:57:32.000 --> 00:57:34.000
You don't necessarily have to throw those examples out.

00:57:34.000 --> 00:57:38.000
Instead, you can use some kind of algorithm like nearest neighbors

00:57:38.000 --> 00:57:40.000
or just a plain old median or, you know,

00:57:40.000 --> 00:57:44.000
there's lots of different ways to impute missing data that you have.

00:57:44.000 --> 00:57:47.000
You can perform dimensionality reduction.

00:57:47.000 --> 00:57:53.000
So you can say you had a lot of features, just a lot, too many, in fact,

00:57:53.000 --> 00:57:54.000
one might say.

00:57:54.000 --> 00:57:57.000
One thing to do is to use an unsupervised approach,

00:57:57.000 --> 00:57:59.000
like maybe there's structure in there.

00:57:59.000 --> 00:58:01.000
Some of them are correlated with each other.

00:58:02.000 --> 00:58:06.000
You can use dimensionality reduction to project that high dimensional space,

00:58:06.000 --> 00:58:10.000
lots and lots of predictors, down to a lower dimensional space.

00:58:10.000 --> 00:58:14.000
And then you can use a model estimation, you know,

00:58:14.000 --> 00:58:19.000
algorithm like linear regression or, you know, anything like that,

00:58:19.000 --> 00:58:22.000
to then learn your outcome from your inputs.

00:58:22.000 --> 00:58:25.000
So there's just a lot more.

00:58:25.000 --> 00:58:30.000
I think, you know, when I talked about models at the beginning,

00:58:30.000 --> 00:58:34.000
you're like, oh, my gosh, there's so many models out there.

00:58:34.000 --> 00:58:41.000
How, like, I have to try a bunch of them to see what might work best.

00:58:41.000 --> 00:58:45.000
I feel like there's even more options that things do when it comes to feature

00:58:45.000 --> 00:58:48.000
engineering, but on the positive side for that,

00:58:48.000 --> 00:58:51.000
usually you know more about your data.

00:58:51.000 --> 00:58:55.000
And feature engineering is really a place where often we use our domain

00:58:55.000 --> 00:58:59.000
knowledge by how to create these better features.

00:58:59.000 --> 00:59:02.000
And what tidy models lets us do is to, you know,

00:59:02.000 --> 00:59:09.000
to write something like this where we write with a series of steps,

00:59:09.000 --> 00:59:14.000
how do I need to get from my beginning data to my data that is ready to go

00:59:14.000 --> 00:59:18.000
into a model, some kind of machine learning algorithm.

00:59:18.000 --> 00:59:20.000
So here, notice, we normalize,

00:59:20.000 --> 00:59:22.000
and then we're doing principal component analysis,

00:59:22.000 --> 00:59:25.000
which is a kind of dimensionality reduction here.

00:59:25.000 --> 00:59:28.000
So the output of that, well, okay, let's say,

00:59:28.000 --> 00:59:33.000
so here's this recipe, I can put that recipe together with a model.

00:59:33.000 --> 00:59:35.000
And the recommended way we do that,

00:59:35.000 --> 00:59:37.000
we have for doing this is in what's called a workflow.

00:59:37.000 --> 00:59:40.000
A workflow, a modeling workflow,

00:59:40.000 --> 00:59:43.000
puts together the components that you need to,

00:59:43.000 --> 00:59:50.000
that you have in a connected thing that you can then walk around with

00:59:50.000 --> 00:59:54.000
and use, for example, within resampling.

00:59:54.000 --> 00:59:58.000
So here, what I'm doing is I'm just, I'm fitting it to my training data.

00:59:58.000 --> 01:00:03.000
So notice here that the coefficients of my model are those principal

01:00:03.000 --> 01:00:08.000
components, those principal components that I learned.

01:00:08.000 --> 01:00:12.000
So, you know, I started with like more features,

01:00:12.000 --> 01:00:14.000
like what I showed you in the,

01:00:14.000 --> 01:00:17.000
at the beginning when I was talking about spending your data budget.

01:00:17.000 --> 01:00:20.000
And at the end, what I actually predict my,

01:00:20.000 --> 01:00:22.000
what I fit my model with is with these.

01:00:22.000 --> 01:00:24.000
And then I can also predict with those,

01:00:24.000 --> 01:00:28.000
even with my input data as it is.

01:00:28.000 --> 01:00:32.000
So we put those things together in a way that lets us use,

01:00:32.000 --> 01:00:39.000
lets us have good statistical process through that whole thing.

01:00:39.000 --> 01:00:41.000
So there is lots more to learn.

01:00:41.000 --> 01:00:45.000
These, in terms of actually using tidy models,

01:00:45.000 --> 01:00:50.000
I really like thinking about focusing on these three items as things that

01:00:50.000 --> 01:00:55.000
might be motivating for you to think about whether tidy models is a good

01:00:55.000 --> 01:00:57.000
fit for your particular use case.

01:00:57.000 --> 01:01:01.000
I mean, they are very common things that we run into like, oh,

01:01:01.000 --> 01:01:05.000
I don't ahead of time know which kind of model I should use.

01:01:05.000 --> 01:01:07.000
Oh, I have a limited amount of data.

01:01:07.000 --> 01:01:12.000
I need to make sure I'm using it responsibly so that I'm not fooled into

01:01:12.000 --> 01:01:15.000
thinking my model is going to perform better than it does in the end.

01:01:15.000 --> 01:01:19.000
Or I need, I really got to do some feature engineering,

01:01:19.000 --> 01:01:25.000
some pre-processing of my data to get it ready for my modeling.

01:01:25.000 --> 01:01:29.000
These are very common and great things to keep in mind as you might want to,

01:01:29.000 --> 01:01:32.000
as you might want to think about what modeling approach you'll take.

