how does it work for time series modeling?

01:02:52.000 --> 01:02:54.000
So there are some,

01:02:54.000 --> 01:02:57.000
one great thing about no longer sharing is I can find links easier.

01:02:57.000 --> 01:03:04.000
There are methods for a time-based data.

01:03:05.000 --> 01:03:09.000
So there, I think a lot of the, there's a couple of them,

01:03:09.000 --> 01:03:10.000
a couple of different kinds,

01:03:10.000 --> 01:03:14.000
probably the one that you would want to use the most are these sliding

01:03:14.000 --> 01:03:15.000
windows.

01:03:15.000 --> 01:03:19.000
So if you picture yourself having, you know,

01:03:19.000 --> 01:03:22.000
picture yourself having a hundred time series data.

01:03:22.000 --> 01:03:26.000
So the way that you do cross-validation with time series data is that you

01:03:26.000 --> 01:03:31.000
make these sliding windows and you train on,

01:03:31.000 --> 01:03:36.000
on say the first part of the window and then about a test on the second

01:03:36.000 --> 01:03:38.000
bit, and then you move it down like this.

01:03:38.000 --> 01:03:43.000
And then that helped that like gives you say, if you did 10 folds,

01:03:43.000 --> 01:03:44.000
10 sliding windows,

01:03:44.000 --> 01:03:47.000
you get then get 10 estimates of performance and you can aggregate those.

01:03:47.000 --> 01:03:49.000
If you're out how, how it goes.

01:03:49.000 --> 01:03:51.000
So those are the sliding windows.

01:03:51.000 --> 01:03:55.000
The other ones are the, a rolling origin,

01:03:55.000 --> 01:03:57.000
which is a little bit, it works.

01:03:57.000 --> 01:04:01.000
It works slightly different than the sliding window,

01:04:01.000 --> 01:04:03.000
but there are these different,

01:04:03.000 --> 01:04:06.000
these different methods for when you have time series data.

01:04:06.000 --> 01:04:08.000
The other thing to keep in mind is you need,

01:04:08.000 --> 01:04:13.000
you need different approaches when you have spatial data.

01:04:13.000 --> 01:04:18.000
With both spatial data and with time, time series data,

01:04:18.000 --> 01:04:21.000
the thing is that objects that are close together,

01:04:21.000 --> 01:04:24.000
either in space or time are more similar.

01:04:25.000 --> 01:04:28.000
Then then in random, like they have, you know,

01:04:28.000 --> 01:04:30.000
it's called auto correlation.

01:04:30.000 --> 01:04:32.000
Like things are similar things that are,

01:04:32.000 --> 01:04:34.000
that are near each other are similar to each other.

01:04:34.000 --> 01:04:39.000
So you have to do a slightly like more careful job of data splitting so that

01:04:39.000 --> 01:04:44.000
you do not get again, fooled into thinking you have better performance than

01:04:44.000 --> 01:04:45.000
